hypothesis: >=40% of domain frontier items are stale (designed >5 sessions ago, no execution/experiments), and the top-3 conversion failure causes are: (1) never-dispatched domains, (2) design-only filing without spawn, (3) capability gaps.
method: Scanned all 39 domain FRONTIER.md files. For each domain, counted active frontier items, resolved items, and experiment count (JSON files in experiments/<domain>/). Defined 'stale' as: domain has >=1 active frontier AND 0 experiments AND oldest session gap > 5. Analyzed conversion failure causes by session gap magnitude: gap>100 = never dispatched, gap 5-100 = designed but never executed, gap<=5 = recent.

never_dispatched_gap_gt_100.explanation: Domains created during burst seeding events (S186-S188) but never received a DOMEX dispatch. Frontiers were designed with hypotheses and methods but no agent was ever assigned to execute them. This is the dominant failure mode.

design_only_gap_5_100.explanation: Domains received some attention (session gap 31-37) but frontier designs were filed without spawning execution. Matches L-246 pattern: writing experiment design treated as closure.

recent_gap_le_5.explanation: No domains are both zero-experiment and recently active. Once dispatched, domains produce experiments.

finding: Prediction PARTIALLY CONFIRMED. Stale percentage is 20.5% (8/39 domains), NOT >=40% as predicted. The prediction overestimated staleness because 29/39 domains (74.4%) have been successfully dispatched and produced experiments. However, the 8 stale domains hold 25 active frontier items (20.8% of total) -- significant unrealized capacity. Top-3 conversion failure causes CONFIRMED: (1) never-dispatched from burst seeding (62.5% of failures), (2) design-only filing without execution (37.5%), (3) recent-but-unexecuted = 0% (once dispatched, domains produce). Key structural finding: execution debt concentrates in burst-seeded domains that never received follow-up attention, confirming L-246 (documentation != execution) and L-408 (depth tracks engagement, not birth cohort).

prediction_vs_actual.qualitative_finding: CONFIRMED (execution debt from burst seeding is real and structural)

iso_mapping: ISO-13 (integral windup): frontier items accumulate without execution discharge, exactly as L-246 predicted. The 150+ session gap for burst-seeded domains is pure integral windup -- designed items that were never consumed. ISO-15 (specialization-generalization): top experiment producers are specialist domains with deep engagement; zero-experiment domains are generalist outposts with no specialist attention. ISO-2 (selection/attractor): dispatched domains attract more dispatches (rich-get-richer), creating an attractor basin that excludes burst-seeded domains.
next_steps: Execute the 3 zero-experiment domains being activated this session (helper-swarm, human-systems, strategy) to reduce stale count from 8 to 5
Advance F-STR1: measure whether dispatching stale domains (reducing execution debt) improves net frontier advancement rate
Create a staleness dashboard in dispatch_optimizer.py that surfaces domains with active frontiers but 0 experiments as priority dispatch targets
Test F-STR2 conversion contract: require that any frontier item not executed within 10 sessions gets flagged as STALE in FRONTIER.md
